 Arduino Uno

The Arduino Uno is one of the most popular microcontroller development boards used in electronics, robotics, automation, and embedded systems. It is based on the **ATmega328P** microcontroller and provides an easy-to-use platform for learning programming and hardware interfacing.



📦 Basic Features

| Feature                     | Value      |
| --------------------------- | ---------- |
| Microcontroller             | ATmega328P |
| Operating Voltage           | 5V         |
| Input Voltage (Recommended) | 7V – 12V   |
| Digital I/O Pins            | 14         |
| PWM Pins                    | 6          |
| Analog Inputs               | 6          |
| Flash Memory                | 32 KB      |
| SRAM                        | 2 KB       |
| EEPROM                      | 1 KB       |
| Clock Speed                 | 16 MHz     |

🔹 ATmega328P Microcontroller

The main processor of the Arduino Uno. It executes uploaded programs and controls all input/output operations.

🔹 Operating Voltage (5V)

The board operates internally at 5 volts. Digital HIGH signals are approximately 5V.

🔹 Clock Speed (16 MHz)

The microcontroller executes approximately 16 million instruction cycles per second.

🔹 Flash Memory (32 KB)

Stores the uploaded program permanently until a new program is uploaded.

🔹 SRAM (2 KB)

Temporary memory used while the program is running.

🔹 EEPROM (1 KB)

Non-volatile memory used to store data permanently, even after power is removed.



